1
00:00:00,380 --> 00:00:03,150
A lot of times you'll be working
with projects that require

2
00:00:03,150 --> 00:00:07,030
different library versions or
different versions of python even.

3
00:00:07,030 --> 00:00:11,580
In my experience and in many other
people's' it's really difficult to get

4
00:00:11,580 --> 00:00:14,370
all these versions to play
nicely together on one computer.

5
00:00:15,510 --> 00:00:19,220
To solve this problem we use virtual
environments managed with libraries such

6
00:00:19,220 --> 00:00:21,000
as Virtualenv.

7
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:23,970
Virtual environments let you
separate libraries required by

8
00:00:23,970 --> 00:00:26,530
different projects, so
you can avoid conflicts.

9
00:00:28,060 --> 00:00:31,720
If you're working with data though,
Anaconda is the way to go.

10
00:00:31,720 --> 00:00:35,900
Anaconda is a distribution of libraries
and software specifically built for

11
00:00:35,900 --> 00:00:36,560
data science.

12
00:00:38,540 --> 00:00:40,380
It comes with Conda, a package and

13
00:00:40,380 --> 00:00:44,310
environment manager that will make
your life a thousand times better.

14
00:00:44,310 --> 00:00:47,320
Now I'll show you a bit
about using Conda.

15
00:00:47,320 --> 00:00:51,280
I generally create a new environment for
each project I start,

16
00:00:51,280 --> 00:00:54,770
this way I can keep the necessary
package versions separate.

17
00:00:54,770 --> 00:00:58,070
For example if I want to start
a new project using Python 3.

18
00:00:58,070 --> 00:01:00,820
Which you should be using for
all new projects,

19
00:01:00,820 --> 00:01:02,892
I can create an environment for it.

20
00:01:02,892 --> 00:01:09,468
Type in conde create,
give it a name, tea_facts.

21
00:01:09,468 --> 00:01:12,244
[BLANK_AUDIO]

22
00:01:12,244 --> 00:01:16,588
It's a bot that tweets
facts about tea and

23
00:01:16,588 --> 00:01:20,690
the python version, three and enter.

24
00:01:20,690 --> 00:01:25,947
[BLANK_AUDIO]

25
00:01:25,947 --> 00:01:27,797
This will create the environment for me.

26
00:01:27,797 --> 00:01:34,976
Now, I can enter the environment
like so, source activate tea_facts.

27
00:01:34,976 --> 00:01:37,560
[BLANK_AUDIO]

28
00:01:37,560 --> 00:01:41,100
This is the command on Mac in Linux,
on Window it's just activate.

29
00:01:42,280 --> 00:01:46,110
Now I'm in the environment,
you can see the name in the prompt.

30
00:01:46,110 --> 00:01:49,220
And you can see here
the packages that are installed,

31
00:01:49,220 --> 00:01:51,300
these are just the default packages.

32
00:01:51,300 --> 00:01:54,100
Now I can start installing
what I want for this projects.

33
00:01:55,290 --> 00:01:59,990
Let's install Numpy Pandas, for working
with the t data and matplotlib for

34
00:01:59,990 --> 00:02:01,539
making visualization.

35
00:02:01,539 --> 00:02:11,539
[BLANK_AUDIO]

36
00:02:16,085 --> 00:02:20,193
Then I'll start notebooks which
I like to use to develop code.

37
00:02:20,193 --> 00:02:30,193
[BLANK_AUDIO]

38
00:02:39,617 --> 00:02:42,910
And again looking at
the installed packages.

39
00:02:42,910 --> 00:02:44,940
I have all these ready to use for
my project.

40
00:02:46,100 --> 00:02:48,620
And these are separated
from other environments, so

41
00:02:48,620 --> 00:02:52,200
I won't run into any
conflicting version issues.

42
00:02:52,200 --> 00:02:55,940
Okay, now it's your turn to learn how
to use Conda for your own projects,

43
00:02:55,940 --> 00:02:59,300
because that thing will take
around 30 minutes up to an hour.

44
00:02:59,300 --> 00:02:59,910
Okay, have fun.
